clinical_study.brief_title: Safety and Efficacy of BI 10773 as add-on to Insulin Regimen in Patients With Type 2 Diabetes Mellitus
clinical_study.official_title: A Phase III, Randomized, Double-blind, Placebo-controlled, Parallel Group Safety and Efficacy Study of BI 10773 (10 mg and 25 mg Administered Orally Once Daily) During 52 Weeks in Patients With Type 2 Diabetes Mellitus and Insufficient Glycemic Control on MDI Insulin Regimen Alone or With Metformin

brief_summary.textblock: This trial will evaluate use of BI 10773 as add-on to insulin regimen alone or with metformin in patients with typr 2 diabetes. Both lowering glucose and HbA1c and reducing the use of insulin in this population would provide significant new information for the BI 10773 use and would offer a potential new therapeutic option in this population.

criteria.textblock:
Inclusion criteria:
1. Diagnosis of T2DM prior to informed consent
2. Male and female patients on diet and exercise regimen who are pre-treated with multiple daily injections (MDI) of insulin alone or in combination with immediate or extended release metformin
3. Stable metformin therapy: daily dose >=1500 mg/day or maximum tolerated dose
4. HbA1c >=7.5% and <=10% at screening
Exclusion criteria:
1. Uncontrolled hyperglycemia with a glucose level >240 mg/dl (>13.3 mmol/L) after an overnight fast during placebo run-in
2. Any contraindications to metformin according to the local label
3. Acute coronary syndrome, stroke or TIA within 3 months prior to informed consent

measure.title: Change From Baseline in HbA1c After 18 Weeks of Treatment
measure.description: The primary endpoint was the change from baseline in HbA1c after 18 weeks of treatment.
measure.population: The analysis was conducted on the full analysis set (FAS) of patients. Values after start of antidiabetic rescue therapy (week 18 definition) were set to missing and last observation carried forward (LOCF-18) was used for imputation of missing values.

analysis.groups_desc: For the primary endpoint, the testing of the superiority hypothesis versus placebo was: Hypothesis test: H0: No difference in change from baseline to Week 18 in HbA1c (%) between Empagliflozin 10 mg and placebo Ha: A difference in change from baseline to Week 18 in HbA1c (%) between Empagliflozin 10 mg and placebo
analysis.p_value_desc: Hierarchical testing to adjust for multiple comparisons within each dose level, alpha split equally between the doses (2.5%). Empagliflozin versus placebo change from baseline in HbA1c at week 18 was the first step in each hierarchical sequence.
analysis.method_desc: ANCOVA Model includes baseline HbA1c as a covariate and baseline eGFR, geographic region, baseline background medication, treatment as fixed effects.
analysis.estimate_desc: Estimated value = Adjusted mean of Empagliflozin 10 mg - Adjusted mean of placebo.

outcome.population: Per Protocol Set-patients in FAS without important protocol violations leading to exclusion, completed minimum treatment of 357 days and did not prematurely discontinue. At each visit adverse events were recorded on a cumulative case report form.
